type="local"
addr="jean-goubault-larrecq">Jean Goubault-Larrecq</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:meta
name="source"><fr:strong>Lemma 4.2.5</fr:strong> of ???</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  Let <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> be a topological space. Every open subset <fr:tex>U  \in   \mathcal {O}( X )</fr:tex> is
  <fr:link
href="axt-001Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Z">upward closed</fr:link> with respect to its <fr:link
href="axt-0030.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-0030">specialization
  preorder</fr:link>.
</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>722</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>11</fr:month><fr:day>2</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jean-goubault-larrecq.xml"
type="local"
addr="jean-goubault-larrecq">Jean Goubault-Larrecq</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>axt-002Z</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  Direct by the definition of the specialization preorder.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1362</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon><fr:addr>axt-002K</fr:addr><fr:route>axt-002K.xml</fr:route><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  Let <fr:tex>D</fr:tex> be an <fr:link
href="axt-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001S">algebraic dcpo</fr:link> and <fr:tex>U  \subseteq  D</fr:tex> a Scott open
  subset. We then have
  <fr:tex
display="block">U =  \bigcup   \{   { \uparrow } c   \mid  c  \in  U, c \  \mathsf {compact}  \} .</fr:tex></fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1016</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:parent>axt-002K</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p><fr:tex>( \impliedby )</fr:tex> This direction follows directly from the <fr:link
href="axt-001Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Z">upward
    closure</fr:link> of <fr:tex>U</fr:tex>, which is entailed by its <fr:link
href="axt-001Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Y">Scott
    openness</fr:link>.
  </fr:p>
  <fr:p><fr:tex>( \implies )</fr:tex> Let <fr:tex>x  \in  U</fr:tex>. We need to show that there exists a compact
    <fr:tex>c  \in  U</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>x  \in   { \uparrow } c</fr:tex>. Thanks to the
    <fr:link
href="axt-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001S">algebraicity</fr:link> of <fr:tex>D</fr:tex>, we know that
    <fr:tex>x =  \bigvee ^{ \uparrow }  \{  c  \in   \mathcal {K} (D)  \mid  c  \sqsubseteq  x  \} .</fr:tex>
    The fact that <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="axt-001Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Y">Scott open</fr:link> entails it is inaccessible by
    directed joins so the fact that
    <fr:tex
display="block">\left ( \bigvee ^{ \uparrow }  \{  c  \in   \mathcal {K} (D)  \mid  c  \sqsubseteq  x  \} \right )  \in  U</fr:tex>
    means there exists a compact <fr:tex>c_0  \in  U</fr:tex> with <fr:tex>c_0  \sqsubseteq  x</fr:tex>
    which is to say <fr:tex>x  \in   { \uparrow } c_0</fr:tex>.
  </fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1363</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>axt-001Y</fr:addr><fr:route>axt-001Y.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Scott open subset of a dcpo</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>26</fr:day></fr:date></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  Let <fr:tex>(D,  \sqsubseteq )</fr:tex> be a dcpo. A subset <fr:tex>U  \subseteq  D</fr:tex> is called a
  <fr:em>Scott open</fr:em> if it satisfies the following conditions.
  <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="axt-001Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Z"><fr:strong>upwards-closed</fr:strong></fr:link>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is <fr:strong>inaccessible by directed joins</fr:strong>, which is to say
      for any directed subset <fr:tex>S  \subseteq  D</fr:tex>, if <fr:tex>( { \bigvee }^{ \uparrow } S )  \in  U</fr:tex>
      then there is some <fr:tex>x  \in  S</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>x  \in  U</fr:tex>.
    </fr:li></fr:ol></fr:p><fr:p>
  The definition here follows the definition at the beginning of <fr:strong>Section 2.2</fr:strong>
  of <fr:link
href="michael-smyth.xml"
type="local"
addr="michael-smyth">Mike Smyth</fr:link>'s <fr:link
href="smyth-topology.xml"
type="local"
addr="smyth-topology">handbook chapter on topology</fr:link>.
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1364</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>axt-005Q</fr:addr><fr:route>axt-005Q.xml</fr:route><fr:meta
name="date-added">2024-04-20</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  Let <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> be a set equipped with a preorder <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>. The <fr:link
href="axt-0030.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-0030">specialization
  preorder</fr:link> of the <fr:link
href="axt-003U.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-003U">Alexandroff topology</fr:link> on <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> coincides
  with the order <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>.
</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>304</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:parent>axt-005Q</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>
  The <fr:link
href="axt-0030.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-0030">specialization preorder</fr:link> in the context of the <fr:link
href="axt-003U.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-003U">Alexandroff topology</fr:link>
  amounts to:
  <fr:tex
display="block">x  \le _{ \uparrow } y   \vcentcolon \equiv   \forall  U  \in   \operatorname { \uparrow }( A ) . \  x  \in  U  \rightarrow  y  \in  U .</fr:tex></fr:p>
  <fr:p>
  (<fr:tex>\Rightarrow</fr:tex>) Let <fr:tex>x, y  \in  A</fr:tex> with <fr:tex>x  \le  y</fr:tex> and consider an arbitrary
  <fr:tex>U  \in   \operatorname { \uparrow }( A )</fr:tex> containing <fr:tex>x</fr:tex>. Because <fr:tex>y  \ge  x</fr:tex> it is immediate that
  <fr:tex>y  \in  U</fr:tex> by the <fr:link
href="axt-001Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Z">upward closure</fr:link> of <fr:tex>U</fr:tex>.
  </fr:p>
  <fr:p>
  (<fr:tex>\Leftarrow</fr:tex>) Let <fr:tex>x, y  \in  A</fr:tex> with <fr:tex>x  \le _{ \uparrow } y</fr:tex>. The principal
  filter <fr:tex>\operatorname { \uparrow }( x )</fr:tex> must be an open in the Alexandroff topology as it is
  upward closed. Since <fr:tex>x  \in   \operatorname { \uparrow }( x )</fr:tex>, we immediately have <fr:tex>y  \in     \operatorname { \uparrow }( x )</fr:tex> by the definition of <fr:tex>\le _{ \uparrow }</fr:tex>. which is to say <fr:tex>x  \le  y</fr:tex>.
  </fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
