  Let <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> be a set equipped with a preorder <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>. The <fr:link
href="axt-003U.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-003U">Alexandroff
  topology</fr:link> on <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="axt-005U.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-005U">finer</fr:link> than any topology whose specialization
  preorder coincides with <fr:tex>( \le )</fr:tex>.
</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>306</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:parent>axt-005R</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  Let <fr:tex>\mathcal {T}</fr:tex> be a topology on <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> such that the specialization preorder
  <fr:tex>\le _{ \mathcal {T}}</fr:tex> coincides with the order <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex>U  \subseteq  A</fr:tex> be
  a <fr:tex>\mathcal {T}</fr:tex>-open. The open subset <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> must be <fr:link
href="axt-001Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Z">upward closed</fr:link> with
  respect to <fr:tex>\le _{ \mathcal {T}}</fr:tex> by <fr:link
href="axt-002Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-002Z">axt-002Z</fr:link>. Since <fr:tex>\le _ \mathcal {T}</fr:tex> coincides
  with <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>, this means that <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is upward closed with respect to the
  order <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>, which is to say it is an Alexandroff open.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
